Part 2 — Business Insights

Insight 1: Cancellation Rate Is Structurally High — 37.58%

At 37.58%, the cancellation rate is nearly double the lower end of the hospitality industry benchmark (20–30%). This is not an anomaly — it is a structural feature of the booking mix.


Hotel	Total Bookings	Cancellations	Cancel Rate
City Hotel	78,197	33,078	42.30%
Resort Hotel	39,379	11,110	28.21%
Overall	117,576	44,188	37.58%

City Hotel's cancellation rate is 50% higher than Resort Hotel's. As City Hotel represents 66.5% of total bookings, it disproportionately pulls up the blended rate.


Business implication: Any revenue forecast using total ADR x total bookings will overstate actual revenue by ~37.58%. Always use adr_adjusted and estimated_revenue (set to $0 for canceled bookings) for revenue projections. Apply WHERE is_canceled = false for all operational metrics.



Insight 2: Lead Time Is a Near-Perfect Cancellation Predictor

The relationship between booking lead time and cancellation rate is near-linear and extremely strong.


Lead Time Window	Bookings	Cancellation Rate	Avg ADR	Avg Nights
Same Day (0 days)	5,797	7.19%	$91.12	1.63
1-30 days	31,569	21.38%	$104.47	2.75
31-90 days	29,322	37.99%	$107.19	3.58
91-180 days	26,321	44.90%	$109.60	4.09
181-365 days	21,436	55.66%	$95.55	4.15
365+ days	3,131	68.00%	$79.24	2.59

Bookings made more than a year in advance cancel at 9.5x the rate of same-day bookings. The highest-ADR bookings (91-180 day window, $109.60) sit squarely in the middle-risk cancellation band.


Business implication: Lead time should be the primary input in dynamic deposit policy. Requiring a non-refundable or partial deposit for bookings over 90 days out could significantly reduce the cancellation tail. Over half (55.66%) of bookings in the 181-365 day band will not convert.



Insight 3: City Hotel Carries 2x More Volume and 50% More Cancellation Risk

Metric	City Hotel	Resort Hotel
Total Bookings	78,197 (66.5%)	39,379 (33.5%)
Cancellation Rate	42.30%	28.21%
Raw ADR	$106.74	$96.59
Total Revenue	$14,385,342 (55.4%)	$11,601,634 (44.6%)
Avg Length of Stay	2.99 nights	4.37 nights
Avg Lead Time	110.9 days	93.4 days

Despite a higher raw ADR, City Hotel's revenue advantage is compressed by its 42.3% cancellation rate. Resort Hotel guests book closer to arrival (93 vs 111 days), stay 46% longer, and cancel far less — a more predictable revenue profile.


Business implication: Resort Hotel is the more stable revenue base. City Hotel drives volume but requires aggressive revenue management (overbooking, shorter cancellation windows, deposit requirements) to compensate for its cancellation exposure.



