Summer ADR has escalated significantly year-over-year:


Month	2015	2016	2017	Growth
July	$99.89	$127.16	$144.13	+44%
August	$108.46	$144.07	$165.15	+52%

The lowest ADR month was November 2015 ($62.23). The highest was August 2017 ($165.15) — a 165% spread between seasonal trough and peak.


Business implication: Summer pricing power is well established and growing. The November-January trough ($62-$88 ADR) is the primary revenue opportunity — promotions, package bundles, or conference/event targeting could lift the winter floor rate.



Insight 8: Bed and Breakfast Dominates — But Full Board Cancels at 61%

Meal Plan	Bookings	Share	Cancel Rate	Avg ADR	Revenue
Bed and Breakfast (BB)	90,955	77.36%	37.93%	$100.83	$18,669,541
Half Board (HB)	14,277	12.14%	34.88%	$121.87	$5,034,460
Self Catering (SC)	10,428	8.87%	37.84%	$100.24	$1,669,809
None	1,133	0.96%	25.24%	$94.87	$381,491
Full Board (FB)	783	0.67%	61.05%	$111.13	$231,675

Half Board guests pay a 21% ADR premium over Bed and Breakfast ($121.87 vs $100.83) and cancel slightly less (34.88% vs 37.93%). Full Board — the most comprehensive package — paradoxically cancels at 61%, the highest rate of any meal type.


Business implication: Half Board is the optimal upsell target — higher ADR, lower cancellation, meaningful volume. Full Board bookings carry significant risk; pair FB offerings with tighter deposit requirements or shorter cancellation windows.



